Back to Lake Louise this weekend to watch potentially the last Women’s World Cup Event in western Canada. It’s bitter sweet as Lake Louise is such a great course and has become an iconic race on the tour. But, in exchange, the race organizers at Mount Tremblant will surely put on an amazing race that will not only become an an epic race on tour, but has a large enough village to create the party and exciting environment the event deserves. Thank you to all the amazing volunteers at Lake Louise!!! You made this event one of a kind❤️!

I’m a ski racing fan!

A little story about me; when I grew up, my stepdad Bill had a few old VHSs that Alpine Canada and @pierruel put together for the season’s winning runs. Much like today, that video would consist of mainly @mikaelashiffrin, @akilde and @marcoodermatt, so in my day, I spent my time watching Herman Maier and Michael Von Grünigen's win time and time again. It’s all I knew. I knew a winning run was a fine line between a foundation of perfected skiing on the edge of imperfection. So I based my approach on attaining these qualities. Little did I know that others were part of the race striving with all their might, as I never had the chance to watch an entire race, only the winning run. It was only when I started racing World Cup that I learnt the names of the other racers and the skills they possessed. I later realized that winning wasn’t the norm, but the exception to the few that learn to best asses risk, practice with intent and become comfortable with being uncomfortable. I spent most of my first seasons on World Cup studying why people lose and less so focusing on the winners, and this is how I became a fan of ski racing. In my eyes, all the racers are heroes, from 10 years old to World Cup winners, and this is because these individuals have chosen to put themselves in a position of the discomfort of uncertainty and self-doubt in their efforts to experience their best. So although I am a fan of winning, I am also a fan of all the athletes becoming their best. I am a fan of ski racing! 

📸 @brondmo

Hey everyone 👋. Those that know me well know that the scariest part of my ski days are dealing with my fear of heights. As we are fast approaching the best days to be out on the slopes I partnered with @technicalsafetybc in offering a quick refresher on loading the chair. 

First off, I know loading a lift while skiing can be intimidating, but it can be a smooth and easy process with the right technique. Here are some tips to help you and your kids this weekend.  .. Look towards the outside of the chair, or if the chair is a double with a pole in the center, look towards the pole. This will help you align yourself with the chair when loading.
 
When loading with kids, ask the lift attendant to slow down the chair if needed. Kids should load the chair positioned beside the attendant. If you are loading with two children, ask the attendant to help you load one of the children.
 
 Once you reach the loading area, sit back on the chair and keep your skis pointed forward. Keep your poles in your lap  Sit back in  the chair, with your butt as far back in the seat as possible.  Lastly, use the safety bar and lower it as soon as you sit down. This will help keep you safe and secure during the ride.
 
Please! Don’t let a chairlift accident ruin your experience on the slopes. 😎🙌⛷️🏂

#technicalsafetybc #TSBC #Chairliftsafety #skilift #chairlift #ad

The kids broke out my helmet collection tonight. All 76 of them. 

I started this collection after a trip to @marco_buechel’s house where I noticed he had a few old helmets kicking around. In Canada we grew up trading hockey cards, with the most sought after cards being the custom painted goalie helmets. So, when the guys and girls on the World Cup started painting their helmets I thought it would be a great idea to ask if anyone had an old race helmet laying around. Fast forward to today, I now have 76 helmets from 69 athletes.

The prerequisite of being in the collection is the athlete needs a World Cup podium, and a custom painted helmet. They also needed to have signed the helmet to me😀. It was always a pain in the ass collecting these helmets while travelling around Europe needing another bag to drag around, but now that I’m retired, these helmets mean the world to me and tell such a unique story. Stories I can share with my kids!

Back in Aspen last weekend for @directors_cup_ski things got weird

I have been told by many people ‘it’s not every day a ski racer graduates’. Haha, well, June 9th one sure did! 

I tell ya, a growth mindset has sure helped me create and achieve a lot of goals in my life. But damn, these ideas add up to a lot of work! 

It’s been one wild ride pivoting life from living in the gym, to living in the books. School has always been a struggle for me, but I knew if I could harness all the acumen I had acquired in my sport career it could be accomplished. So I did, then I did it! 

Thank you to my wife for being by my side. The long nights and weekends were a grind for both of us as I pushed through projects and she took care of the kids! 

Lastly, as a quick fyi; I do think making money before attending university is a sweet way to do it! 

#bcomm #degree #studentathlete

Back in NYC to visit some old friends❤️. 

Most people don’t know this, but I spent an off-season training in New York. Post the 2010 Olympics, Alpine Canada’s high-performance program was imploding by the second. In my mission to not be collateral damage, I set out to find a high-quality and demanding program. After reaching out to many athletes, Steve Nash introduced me to his trainer in NYC. The program fit my goals, so off I went. 

It has been a minute since I’ve been to the city, and man, it has my heart!

Went on a fabulous multi-night adventure with some of my favourite people🏔️🏕️🙌!

Over the past few years while I’ve been working on rehabbing my leg @blastgirl has become quite the hiker. From hiking the highest peaks to embarking on massive weeklong adventures. So naturally I was over the moon when she invited me to join her on an adventure. 

With all my years as a skier in the mountains, I’ve been more of an “Inbounds” kinda guy. So Lana helped me get all of my stuff ready. I figured out what I needed to buy, and what I should borrow. So we packed up and headed to the trail head. However, to my surprise, when we started hiking at 8:30 in the morning, I asked “when do you think we’ll get there?” To which she responded “I think around 5:30.”😳 All of this planning and I forgot to ask the most important question!!! how long will this take?!? 

Well we made it and it was such a fun adventure!

Dustin Cook teaching my kids about hard work! 

Which brings me to a quote a once heard “To raise kids with grit, let them ski. They'll soon learn, that going uphill requires sweat and persistence, and you can skip that step by using the ski lift.” 

Hmmm, or maybe I made that up!?! 🤣

Flying 89meters! 

The other day I was a guest on the @americandownhiller podcast. On the pod I told a story  about the Camel jumps in @skiworldcupvalgardena and how in one of the training runs I boosted off the gap jump and measured a flight of 89meters. It was so big that the course crew delayed the run after my jump to take off the lip. During that time the coaching staff went over to my landing spot and measured the flight. The flight was a mix of the Camels being quite big that year, the training run skiing well over 120km/h at the takeoff, mixed with mostly a lack of skill on my part being new to the World Cup. 

Anyway, my service man and long time friend @dou8le_g  sent me the photo of this jump this morning. Whoops! As you can see, Im still cruising in the air where I should be landing. 🤷 I was thankful for young knees!
